00:40:57,822 --> 00:40:59,983
The mean man.

518
00:41:03,294 --> 00:41:05,353
What is that man doing?

519
00:41:05,396 --> 00:41:07,591
Trying to get up.

520
00:41:07,631 --> 00:41:10,794
Trying to get up into our world.

521
00:41:41,599 --> 00:41:43,624
Where's Daddy now?

522
00:41:49,907 --> 00:41:51,568
Daddy's in heaven.

523
00:41:53,444 --> 00:41:55,537
He's with God now.

524
00:41:58,482 --> 00:42:02,851
Do you have to die to see God?

525
00:42:02,887 --> 00:42:04,616
I don't think so.

526
00:42:07,958 --> 00:42:09,721
I think you have to pray.

527
00:42:12,696 --> 00:42:14,527
And reach out.

528
00:42:19,336 --> 00:42:22,703
Why does God let there
be bad things?

529
00:42:25,976 --> 00:42:28,501
I honestly don't know, honey.

530
00:42:31,615 --> 00:42:33,640
Please try to get some sleep.

531
00:42:43,661 --> 00:42:46,323
Can you come with me
in my dreams?

532
00:42:50,734 --> 00:42:53,430
I think that only
happens in the movies.

533
00:42:55,773 --> 00:42:59,004
But I'll always, always...

534
00:42:59,043 --> 00:43:01,375
be right here when you get back.

535
00:43:03,480 --> 00:43:09,350
And I'll make sure
that nobody gets your toes.

536
00:43:59,169 --> 00:44:02,297
I know his behavior
is bizarre...

537
00:44:02,339 --> 00:44:04,899
but he's usually so normal
and well adjusted, John...

538
00:44:04,942 --> 00:44:06,136
I can't believe it's him...

539
00:44:06,176 --> 00:44:09,043
and not something outside
influencing him.

540
00:44:10,180 --> 00:44:12,512
Or is that how denial works?

541
00:44:13,584 --> 00:44:14,915
It is denial.

542
00:44:14,952 --> 00:44:17,682
I don't think
that's the case here.

543
00:44:17,721 --> 00:44:19,382
If you're really worried
about Dylan...

544
00:44:19,423 --> 00:44:21,414
have a doctor check him out.

545
00:44:21,458 --> 00:44:23,050
You'll see. Everything's fine.

546
00:44:23,093 --> 00:44:26,893
You're not just saying that
to help a crazy friend cope?

547
00:44:28,799 --> 00:44:31,495
Everything about Dylan's
behavior is understandable...

548
00:44:31,535 --> 00:44:34,698
for a kid
who just lost his father.

549
00:44:34,738 --> 00:44:38,265
How does a child
process a thing like that?

550
00:44:38,308 --> 00:44:39,935
I don't know.

551
00:44:41,311 --> 00:44:44,337
I've not been able
to process it very well myself.

552
00:44:44,381 --> 00:44:47,214
And you're not crazy,
by the way.

553
00:44:47,251 --> 00:44:50,778
Seeing Freddy in that grave
and then jumping in...

554
00:44:50,821 --> 00:44:52,015
You didn't jump in.

555
00:44:52,056 --> 00:44:55,184
That's my memory.
It seemed absolutely real.

556
00:44:55,225 --> 00:44:56,692
"Seemed," not "was."

557
00:44:59,830 --> 00:45:02,799
It's in my family, you know.

558
00:45:02,833 --> 00:45:04,824
What is?

559
00:45:04,868 --> 00:45:07,928
A very close relative
died in an institution.

560
00:45:07,971 --> 00:45:12,340
Really? If having a screwy
family made a person crazy...

561
00:45:13,143 --> 00:45:15,577
the whole world
would be one big loony bin.

562
00:45:18,415 --> 00:45:20,940
You have a crazed fan after you.

563
00:45:20,984 --> 00:45:24,442
That's what's making you crazy.
Probably Dylan, too.

564
00:45:24,488 --> 00:45:26,115
I never mentioned that to him.

565
00:45:26,156 --> 00:45:29,387
Kids know when something's
bugging the parent.

566
00:45:30,861 --> 00:45:34,228
You have no idea
who this is calling?

567
00:45:34,264 --> 00:45:36,926
- Freddy, for all I know.
- Come on.

568
00:45:37,534 --> 00:45:39,092
He's a man.

569
00:45:40,204 --> 00:45:45,267
Or a boy
with a deep Freddy voice.

570
00:45:45,309 --> 00:45:48,767
Six weeks, and you're surprised
you got Freddy in your dreams?

571
00:45:48,812 --> 00:45:51,178
Hell, Sonny Bono,
after a while...

572
00:45:51,215 --> 00:45:54,446
began seeing his stalker
everywhere, even at Mass.

573
00:45:54,485 --> 00:45:55,645
Really?

574
00:45:56,553 --> 00:45:59,317
How many times
did Letterman call the cops...

575
00:45:59,356 --> 00:46:01,950
thinking that woman
was down in the kitchen again?

576
00:46:03,327 --> 00:46:07,320
Really gets under your skin
if you let it.

577
00:46:12,169 --> 00:46:13,932
You really think Dylan's OK?

578
00:46:13,971 --> 00:46:17,304
Dylan's fine. You're fine.

579
00:46:17,341 --> 00:46:19,366
You're hurting,
but you're fine...

580
00:46:19,409 --> 00:46:21,138
and you're definitely not crazy.

581
00:46:21,845 --> 00:46:23,540
My worst fear...

582
00:46:24,314 --> 00:46:28,045
that whatever madness
is in my family I have...

583
00:46:38,095 --> 00:46:40,222
and I've passed it onto Dylan.

584
00:46:58,949 --> 00:47:01,975
- Make sure he's OK, John.
- Are you all right?

585
00:47:02,019 --> 00:47:04,579
Are you OK? Are you sure?
Does anything hurt?

586
00:47:04,621 --> 00:47:06,384
Dylan, are you all right?

587
00:47:06,423 --> 00:47:09,859
Honey, are you all right?
Are you sure?

588
00:47:09,893 --> 00:47:12,327
God wouldn't take me.

589
00:47:14,865 --> 00:47:17,060
Oh, my God. Oh, honey.

590
00:47:17,100 --> 00:47:18,658
It's unbelievable.

591
00:48:16,660 --> 00:48:19,458
- You doing all right?
- Hanging in there.

592
00:48:19,496 --> 00:48:21,589
You know the guy that was
calling me all the time?

593
00:48:21,632 --> 00:48:23,065
He started again...

594
00:48:23,100 --> 00:48:25,091
and he's putting stuff
in my mail again.

595
00:48:25,135 --> 00:48:27,865
Listen, the S.O.B. Probably
read about the funeral...

596
00:48:27,905 --> 00:48:29,304
in the papers or something.

597
00:48:29,339 --> 00:48:31,637
Sick mother.

598
00:48:31,675 --> 00:48:34,303
That's the last thing
you need right now, I'm sure.

599
00:48:34,344 --> 00:48:37,802
Actually, it's been giving me
Freddy nightmares.

600
00:48:37,848 --> 00:48:40,214
Wait a second.
Now, let me get this straight.

601
00:48:40,250 --> 00:48:44,186
You're having nightmares
about Freddy? As in me?

602
00:48:44,221 --> 00:48:48,453
No. It isn't you. He's scarier.

603
00:48:50,227 --> 00:48:51,387
He's...

604
00:48:52,195 --> 00:48:53,423
Darker?

605
00:48:54,398 --> 00:48:55,524
More evil?

606
00:48:55,565 --> 00:48:58,762
Yeah. How did you know?

607
00:48:58,802 --> 00:49:00,793
Call it a guess.

608
00:49:00,837 --> 00:49:02,896
Pretty damn good guess.

609
00:49:03,907 --> 00:49:06,467
Anyway
what I was calling about was...

610
00:49:06,510 --> 00:49:08,842
have you seen any of the script
by any chance?

611
00:49:08,879 --> 00:49:12,576
No. Wes won't show it
until he's finished.

612
00:49:12,616 --> 00:49:14,208
At least that's what he told me.

613
00:49:14,251 --> 00:49:15,650
When is it gonna be done?

614
00:49:15,686 --> 00:49:18,849
The way he's writing, who knows?

615
00:49:18,889 --> 00:49:20,948
It's so weird.

616
00:49:20,991 --> 00:49:22,856
I asked him how far
he was at the funeral.

617
00:49:22,893 --> 00:49:25,191
What did he say? Oh, yeah.

618
00:49:25,228 --> 00:49:28,254
"As far as Dylan
trying to reach God."

619
00:49:28,298 --> 00:49:31,358
Whatever that means. Weird, huh?

620
00:49:31,401 --> 00:49:34,165
Putting your kid in the script.

621
00:49:34,204 --> 00:49:38,436
Robert...
have you been having nightmares?

622
00:49:42,579 --> 00:49:45,047
Look, we need to talk,
but not over the phone.

623
00:49:45,082 --> 00:49:47,141
Can I come over?

624
00:49:47,184 --> 00:49:52,247
Actually, Heather...
today's no good.

625
00:49:52,289 --> 00:49:56,248
There's something
I have to finish.

626
00:49:56,293 --> 00:49:57,726
Tomorrow maybe, huh?

627
00:49:57,761 --> 00:50:01,026
OK, tomorrow.
But early in the morning.

628
00:50:01,064 --> 00:50:03,726
And meanwhile, Robert,
take care, OK?

629
00:50:04,634 --> 00:50:07,159
Yeah. Sure.

630
00:52:32,782 --> 00:52:33,942
Damn it!

631
00:52:49,199 --> 00:52:54,762
One, two,
Freddy's coming for you

632
00:53:03,914 --> 00:53:08,214
Three, four,
better lock your door

633
00:53:12,289 --> 00:53:16,692
Five, six, grab your crucifix

634
00:53:19,829 --> 00:53:24,266
Seven, eight,
better stay up late

635
00:53:25,435 --> 00:53:28,529
Dylan, don't sing that song.

636
00:53:30,140 --> 00:53:34,634
Nine, ten, never sleep again!

637
00:53:37,981 --> 00:53:40,347
Dylan! Stop it!

638
00:53:41,084 --> 00:53:42,915
No! Don't!

639
00:53:47,290 --> 00:53:49,554
Never sleep again

640
00:53:49,593 --> 00:53:53,324
Never sleep again

641
00:53:53,363 --> 00:53:56,560
Never sleep again

642
00:53:56,600 --> 00:53:59,296
Never sleep again

643
00:54:39,976 --> 00:54:41,136
I touched him.

644
00:55:10,273 --> 00:55:12,673
Any history of epilepsy
in your family?

645
00:55:14,144 --> 00:55:15,338
Diabetes?

646
00:55:17,013 --> 00:55:21,313
Was there a trigger event,
trauma, shock?

647
00:55:21,351 --> 00:55:24,878
You haven't shown him
the films you've made, have you?

648
00:55:24,921 --> 00:55:26,548
The horror stuff?

649
00:55:26,589 --> 00:55:29,080
His father just passed away.

650
00:55:29,125 --> 00:55:31,286
I'm sorry.

651
00:55:32,162 --> 00:55:35,928
But I'm convinced
those films can tip...

652
00:55:35,965 --> 00:55:38,593
an unstable child over the edge.

653
00:55:38,635 --> 00:55:39,897
Unstable?

654
00:55:40,837 --> 00:55:44,068
Dylan's not unstable.
He's just upset.

655
00:55:44,107 --> 00:55:46,735
We'll run a battery of tests
and know in a few days.

656
00:55:46,776 --> 00:55:49,244
Does he have to stay overnight?

657
00:55:49,279 --> 00:55:50,769
Absolutely.

658
00:55:57,287 --> 00:56:00,085
Anything more happen
we need to know about?

659
00:56:01,958 --> 00:56:03,050
Like what?

660
00:56:03,793 --> 00:56:07,627
Sometimes what a child
says or fantasizes...

661
00:56:07,664 --> 00:56:09,928
will give a clue
to what ails him.

662
00:56:09,966 --> 00:56:13,697
Did he say anything
while he was still lucid?

663
00:56:30,420 --> 00:56:32,149
What do we have here?

664
00:56:32,188 --> 00:56:34,748
Too soon to know for sure.

665
00:56:34,791 --> 00:56:38,056
The early symptoms point
to childhood schizophrenia.

666
00:56:42,165 --> 00:56:44,599
Dylan, can you hear me?

667
00:56:46,936 --> 00:56:50,804
Dylan, you have to fight it,
whatever is after you...

668
00:56:50,840 --> 00:56:52,671
and you got to come back to me.

669
00:56:52,709 --> 00:56:55,610
You can't make it alone.
Do you hear?

670
00:56:58,348 --> 00:57:02,182
If you can hear me, tell me
what you need to feel safe.

671
00:57:08,992 --> 00:57:11,460
Rex? Is that what you want?

672
00:57:13,696 --> 00:57:18,656
Well, Rex is at home,
and that's where you should be.

673
00:57:18,701 --> 00:57:22,330
But you got to get better before
they'll let you come home.

674
00:57:22,372 --> 00:57:23,634
Do you understand?

675
00:57:24,974 --> 00:57:27,067
Home.

676
00:57:27,110 --> 00:57:29,908
Home. Home, that's right.

677
00:57:29,946 --> 00:57:32,312
That's where I want you,
sweetie.

678
00:57:32,348 --> 00:57:35,317
And, you know,
we're not that far away.

679
00:57:35,351 --> 00:57:38,377
Look right out there.

680
00:57:38,421 --> 00:57:41,720
Past the freeway is our home.

681
00:57:41,758 --> 00:57:46,855
But to get there, you have to
come out from where you are...

682
00:57:46,896 --> 00:57:50,730
so that they'll let you
come home to Rex.

683
00:57:50,767 --> 00:57:52,200
And to me.

684
00:57:54,003 --> 00:57:55,630
Time for your medicine, cowboy.

685
00:57:56,739 --> 00:57:59,867
- Here you go.
- What is that?

686
00:57:59,909 --> 00:58:01,968
Something to help him sleep.

687
00:58:05,482 --> 00:58:08,645
There you go. It looks good.

688
00:58:14,123 --> 00:58:15,750
There you go.

689
00:58:18,962 --> 00:58:21,522
Good. Good. Attaboy.

690
00:58:21,564 --> 00:58:23,657
Come on,
lie down and take a little nap.

691
00:58:23,700 --> 00:58:25,565
You should get some rest, too.

692
00:58:25,602 --> 00:58:27,934
He's going to be fine.
We're gonna do some tests...

693
00:58:27,971 --> 00:58:29,563
and then
you can come back later.

694
00:58:30,940 --> 00:58:33,704
Can you get
that other side, please?

695
00:58:33,743 --> 00:58:35,711
I grabbed his things.

696
00:58:35,745 --> 00:58:37,975
These are
his favorite pajamas here.

697
00:58:41,551 --> 00:58:43,519
Honey, I've got to go.

698
00:58:43,553 --> 00:58:44,815
I love you, Dylan.

699
00:58:45,788 --> 00:58:47,483
Remember what I said.

700
00:58:49,425 --> 00:58:51,290
We'll take care of everything.

701
00:59:45,748 --> 00:59:47,340
Wake up, lady!

702
00:59:50,653 --> 00:59:52,211
Don't lose it now!

703
01:00:08,671 --> 01:00:10,332
Seismologists at Cal Tech...

704
01:00:10,373 --> 01:00:12,807
have counted
over 300 temblors so far.

705
01:00:12,842 --> 01:00:15,140
Though most were too faint
for us to feel...

706
01:00:15,178 --> 01:00:18,045
seven have shaken our community
in the last few weeks...

707
01:00:18,081 --> 01:00:20,174
and now scientists
are speculating...

708
01:00:20,216 --> 01:00:23,344
there might be an unknown fault
running beneath Los Angeles...

709
01:00:23,386 --> 01:00:24,717
a fault that could...

710
01:00:34,998 --> 01:00:37,558
Hi. You've reached
the Englund residence.

711
01:00:37,600 --> 01:00:38,999
We're out of town.

712
01:00:39,035 --> 01:00:41,469
You can leave a message
if you wish, but...

713
01:00:41,504 --> 01:00:43,938
we'll be gone for some time.

714
01:01:08,698 --> 01:01:10,666
I wish I could tell you
where the script was going.

715
01:01:10,700 --> 01:01:12,167
The fact is I don't know.

716
01:01:12,201 --> 01:01:16,467
I dream a scene at night,
I write it down in the morning.

717
01:01:16,506 --> 01:01:19,031
Beyond that, your guess is as
good as mine where it's going.

718
01:01:19,075 --> 01:01:21,407
At least tell me
what it's about so far.

719
01:01:23,012 --> 01:01:24,980
- Coffee.
- Thanks.

720
01:01:25,014 --> 01:01:27,949
I can tell you what
the nightmare's about so far.

721
01:01:27,984 --> 01:01:32,216
It's about this entity...
whatever you want to call it.

722
01:01:32,255 --> 01:01:34,985
It's old. It's very old.

723
01:01:35,024 --> 01:01:38,619
It's existed in different forms
in different times.

724
01:01:38,661 --> 01:01:41,721
The only thing that stays
the same is what it lives for.

725
01:01:41,764 --> 01:01:43,425
What is that?

726
01:01:43,466 --> 01:01:45,366
The murder of innocents.

727
01:01:46,502 --> 01:01:50,165
This is still a script
we're talking about, right, Wes?

728
01:01:51,741 --> 01:01:55,802
I sort of think of it
as a nightmare in progress.

729
01:01:55,845 --> 01:01:57,642
In this nightmare in progress...

730
01:01:57,680 --> 01:01:59,705
does this thing
have any weaknesses?

731
01:01:59,749 --> 01:02:01,876
It can be captured sometimes.

732
01:02:01,918 --> 01:02:04,216
Captured? How?

733
01:02:04,253 --> 01:02:06,346
By storytellers, of all things.

734
01:02:07,156 --> 01:02:10,216
Every so often, they imagine
a story good enough...

735
01:02:10,259 --> 01:02:12,250
to sort of catch its essence.

736
01:02:12,295 --> 01:02:15,287
Then, for a while,
it's held prisoner in the story.

737
01:02:15,331 --> 01:02:19,563
- Like the genie in the bottle.
- Exactly.

738
01:02:19,602 --> 01:02:21,797
But the problem comes
when the story dies.

739
01:02:21,838 --> 01:02:23,237
And that can happen
in a lot of ways.

740
01:02:23,272 --> 01:02:24,933
It can get too familiar...

741
01:02:24,974 --> 01:02:27,943
or somebody waters it down
to make it an easier sell...

742
01:02:27,977 --> 01:02:32,607
or maybe it's so upsetting
that it's banned outright.

743
01:02:32,648 --> 01:02:35,208
However it happens,
when the story dies...

744
01:02:35,251 --> 01:02:37,412
the evil is set free.

745
01:02:37,453 --> 01:02:41,583
You're saying Freddy
is this ancient thing?

746
01:02:41,624 --> 01:02:44,457
Right. The current version.

747
01:02:44,494 --> 01:02:47,930
And for ten years, he's been
held captive as Freddy...

748
01:02:47,964 --> 01:02:51,024
in the "Nightmare on Elm Street"
series, but...

749
01:02:51,067 --> 01:02:55,470
now that the films have ended,
the genie's out of the bottle.

750
01:02:55,505 --> 01:02:59,464
That's what the nightmares
are telling me and I'm writing.

751
01:02:59,509 --> 01:03:04,276
If Freddy's loose in
your script, where's he going?

752
01:03:04,313 --> 01:03:06,975
Another age? Another form?

753
01:03:07,016 --> 01:03:10,383
No, that's not what
the dreams have him doing.

754
01:03:10,419 --> 01:03:11,852
What is he doing?

755
01:03:13,055 --> 01:03:15,387
He's sort of gotten used
to being Freddy now...

756
01:03:15,424 --> 01:03:18,018
and he likes
our time and space...

757
01:03:18,060 --> 01:03:22,827
so he's decided to cross over
out of films into our reality.

758
01:03:27,003 --> 01:03:29,301
Isn't there somebody
who can stop him?

759
01:03:29,338 --> 01:03:32,830
Actually there is a person
in the dream...

760
01:03:32,875 --> 01:03:35,275
sort of a gatekeeper,
so to speak.

761
01:03:35,311 --> 01:03:38,007
Somebody Freddy has to get by...

762
01:03:38,047 --> 01:03:41,312
before he can
come into our world.

763
01:03:41,350 --> 01:03:44,046
That person's you, Heather.

764
01:03:44,086 --> 01:03:45,451
It's me?

765
01:03:47,356 --> 01:03:48,653
Why me?

766
01:03:48,691 --> 01:03:51,387
Dramatically speaking,
it makes perfect sense.

767
01:03:51,427 --> 01:03:53,054
You played Nancy, after all.

768
01:03:53,095 --> 01:03:55,393
You were the first
to humiliate him, defeat him.

769
01:03:55,431 --> 01:03:58,161
That was Nancy. Not me.

770
01:03:58,201 --> 01:04:01,136
But you gave Nancy her strength.

771
01:04:01,170 --> 01:04:04,298
So in order to get out,
he's got to come through you.

772
01:04:04,340 --> 01:04:08,640
He's gonna try to do that
at your most vulnerable points.

773
01:04:10,513 --> 01:04:12,242
Oh, my God, Wes.

774
01:04:13,316 --> 01:04:14,806
Did you know?

775
01:04:16,552 --> 01:04:19,680
It was a script.
It was a dream.

776
01:04:19,722 --> 01:04:21,883
I didn't know.

777
01:04:21,924 --> 01:04:24,984
You know damn well
it's more than that now.

778
01:04:30,032 --> 01:04:31,499
How can we stop him?

779
01:04:33,202 --> 01:04:35,329
The only way
is to make another movie.

780
01:04:37,406 --> 01:04:39,533
I swear, I'm gonna stay
by this computer...

781
01:04:39,575 --> 01:04:42,510
and keep writing until I finish
the script, but...

782
01:04:42,545 --> 01:04:45,378
when that time comes,
you'll have to make a choice.

783
01:04:45,414 --> 01:04:47,006
Choice?

784
01:04:47,049 --> 01:04:48,539
What kind of choice?

785
01:04:48,584 --> 01:04:51,883
Whether or not you're willing
to play Nancy one last time.

786
01:05:18,180 --> 01:05:21,149
"Many of the symptoms
of childhood schizophrenia...

787
01:05:21,183 --> 01:05:22,650
"are duplicated in children...

788
01:05:22,685 --> 01:05:25,654
"suffering
from sleep deprivation."

789
01:05:32,128 --> 01:05:35,495
"Sleep deprivation can produce
trance-like states...

790
01:05:35,531 --> 01:05:37,658
"mechanical behavior.

791
01:05:37,700 --> 01:05:39,531
"The child might..."

792
01:05:39,568 --> 01:05:41,559
Rex woke me up.

793
01:05:41,604 --> 01:05:44,869
He was fighting the mean old man
with the claws.

794
01:05:44,907 --> 01:05:47,307
You have no idea
who this is calling?

795
01:05:47,343 --> 01:05:48,833
Freddy, for all I know.

796
01:05:48,878 --> 01:05:50,106
As in me?

797
01:05:50,146 --> 01:05:52,876
No, it isn't you. He's scarier.

798
01:05:52,915 --> 01:05:54,746
Darker, more evil?

799
01:05:54,784 --> 01:05:56,115
How did you know?

800
01:05:56,152 --> 01:06:00,179
He's decided to cross over,
out of films, into our reality.

801
01:06:00,222 --> 01:06:03,919
Never sleep again.

802
01:06:15,271 --> 01:06:19,298
The world of horror films
suffered its own terror today...

803
01:06:19,342 --> 01:06:22,607
as two of Hollywood's best known
special-effects technicians...

804
01:06:22,645 --> 01:06:25,273
were found dead
in a vacant field.

805
01:06:25,314 --> 01:06:27,646
Terrance Feinstein
and Charles Wilson...

806
01:06:27,683 --> 01:06:29,412
two special-effects artists...

807
01:06:29,452 --> 01:06:31,716
reputedly working
on a top-secret project...

808
01:06:31,754 --> 01:06:33,949
for the makers of
the Freddy Krueger films...

809
01:06:33,990 --> 01:06:37,858
were found brutally slashed
to death early this morning.

810
01:06:46,736 --> 01:06:47,998
Freddy's glove was missing...

811
01:06:48,037 --> 01:06:50,938
and police are speculating
the murders were the result...

812
01:06:50,973 --> 01:06:52,304
of a botched theft...

813
01:06:52,341 --> 01:06:55,333
which apparently took place
two days ago.

814
01:06:55,378 --> 01:06:58,176
At this point,
the murder weapon has not...

815
01:07:35,184 --> 01:07:36,651
Oh, God.

816
01:08:01,710 --> 01:08:02,904
Miss me?

817
01:08:29,138 --> 01:08:30,935
Nancy.

818
01:08:59,535 --> 01:09:01,332
There are no visiting hours
this late.

819
01:09:01,370 --> 01:09:02,530
You must understand.

820
01:09:02,571 --> 01:09:04,004
No, I don't understand.

821
01:09:04,039 --> 01:09:05,666
I told you I'm his baby-sitter.

822
01:09:05,708 --> 01:09:07,972
I'm a close friend
of the family, damn it.

823
01:09:08,010 --> 01:09:10,240
I just need to see him
for a minute.

824
01:09:10,279 --> 01:09:11,507
Sixty seconds. Come on.

825
01:09:11,547 --> 01:09:13,879
You have to understand.
You can't see him.

826
01:09:16,485 --> 01:09:17,884
What are you doing here?

827
01:09:19,989 --> 01:09:21,149
I don't know.

828
01:09:22,391 --> 01:09:24,791
I had this really terrible dream
about Dylan.

829
01:09:24,827 --> 01:09:27,261
I had to come and see him.

830
01:09:27,296 --> 01:09:29,992
You must think I'm crazy.

831
01:09:30,933 --> 01:09:32,833
No, I don't.

832
01:09:32,868 --> 01:09:34,165
Is he all right?

833
01:09:34,203 --> 01:09:37,070
I don't know.
They wouldn't let me in.

834
01:09:37,106 --> 01:09:40,337
There are no evening visiting
hours in intensive care.

835
01:09:40,376 --> 01:09:41,741
Is he all right?

836
01:09:41,777 --> 01:09:44,177
Dylan? He's holding well.

837
01:09:44,213 --> 01:09:46,147
Earlier he had some problems.

838
01:09:46,182 --> 01:09:49,242
- He's in an oxygen tent now.
- Oh, my God.

839
01:09:52,054 --> 01:09:55,683
Seems we've had an accident,
Miss Langenkamp. May I?

840
01:09:58,060 --> 01:10:00,460
Those are nasty cuts.

841
01:10:00,496 --> 01:10:01,861
How did you get them?

842
01:10:01,897 --> 01:10:05,162
It happened in the earthquake.

843
01:10:05,201 --> 01:10:06,429
I fell.

844
01:10:06,468 --> 01:10:07,992
I need to see Dylan.

845
01:10:08,037 --> 01:10:11,473
In a moment.
First let's see about you.

846
01:10:15,544 --> 01:10:19,674
If these had been a few inches
nearer the wrist...

847
01:10:19,715 --> 01:10:22,240
What did you say
you cut yourself on?

848
01:10:22,284 --> 01:10:24,809
It was the earthquake.
It was dark. I have no idea.

849
01:10:25,621 --> 01:10:27,748
But these look quite fresh.

850
01:10:27,790 --> 01:10:30,657
They are. It happened
in tonight's earthquake.

851
01:10:32,361 --> 01:10:35,159
It happened just 15 minutes ago.

852
01:10:35,197 --> 01:10:36,789
You must have felt it.

853
01:10:39,535 --> 01:10:41,526
Guess we lucked out over here.

854
01:10:44,039 --> 01:10:45,973
Your son...

855
01:10:46,008 --> 01:10:49,409
is apparently
terrified of a man...

856
01:10:49,445 --> 01:10:53,176
someone he thinks
is going to come out of his bed.

857
01:10:53,215 --> 01:10:56,810
One of the nurses heard him
talking to himself.

858
01:10:56,852 --> 01:10:59,821
Do you have any idea
who that man is?

859
01:11:01,223 --> 01:11:03,555
I forgot to bring
his dinosaur Rex.

860
01:11:03,592 --> 01:11:06,857
He keeps Freddy
from coming up out of his...

861
01:11:08,063 --> 01:11:09,587
bed.

862
01:11:09,632 --> 01:11:11,600
The man from your films?

863
01:11:12,901 --> 01:11:14,232
Freddy Krueger?

864
01:11:15,104 --> 01:11:16,366
With the claws?

865
01:11:17,773 --> 01:11:19,502
Is that who he's afraid of?

866
01:11:25,114 --> 01:11:28,413
You have let your child
see your films, haven't you?

867
01:11:28,450 --> 01:11:30,975
Every kid knows who Freddy is.

868
01:11:31,020 --> 01:11:32,988
He's like Santa Claus...

869
01:11:33,022 --> 01:11:34,887
or King Kong or...

870
01:11:37,660 --> 01:11:41,096
Well, interesting talking
with you, Miss Langenkamp.

871
01:11:42,798 --> 01:11:44,527
I hope you understand.

872
01:11:44,566 --> 01:11:47,535
My concerns are simply
for the welfare of your son.

873
01:12:09,191 --> 01:12:10,419
How's he doing?

874
01:12:55,504 --> 01:12:56,869
Honey.

875
01:12:58,440 --> 01:13:00,135
- You shouldn't do that.
- Too late.

876
01:13:01,310 --> 01:13:06,009
I'm almost there, Heather.

877
01:13:06,048 --> 01:13:08,744
Almost there.

878
01:13:14,390 --> 01:13:16,654
Daddy!

879
01:13:25,100 --> 01:13:27,534
- Doctor!
- Keep her right there.

880
01:13:27,569 --> 01:13:29,059
We can't hold him much longer.

881
01:13:29,104 --> 01:13:31,766
Get the full anesthetic, stat.

882
01:13:31,807 --> 01:13:33,206
We don't have that here.

883
01:13:33,242 --> 01:13:36,405
No anesthetic, you say?
Screw it. I'm going in.

884
01:13:36,445 --> 01:13:38,675
Little booger's full of
something I don't like.

885
01:13:39,648 --> 01:13:41,548
Let's get him open,
good and proper.

886
01:13:41,583 --> 01:13:43,380
Cut this evil out of him.

887
01:13:48,290 --> 01:13:50,349
- Gloria!
- He's got my baby!

888
01:13:50,392 --> 01:13:52,326
- Who?
- Freddy!

889
01:13:52,361 --> 01:13:54,090
Who?
Freddy Krueger or something?

890
01:13:54,129 --> 01:13:56,097
- What the hell's going on?
- My baby!

891
01:13:56,131 --> 01:13:58,156
Freddy's got my baby.
He's got my Dylan.

892
01:14:00,235 --> 01:14:03,363
I suggest you go home
and get some rest.

893
01:14:03,405 --> 01:14:04,736
Your son is fine.

894
01:14:04,773 --> 01:14:07,264
He's downstairs
for further testing.

895
01:14:07,309 --> 01:14:08,640
But he was just here.

896
01:14:08,677 --> 01:14:12,579
He was here, you fell asleep,
we took him.

897
01:14:12,614 --> 01:14:14,639
You looked so exhausted...

898
01:14:14,683 --> 01:14:16,742
frankly,
we didn't want to wake you.

899
01:14:16,785 --> 01:14:19,754
Besides, the young woman
Julie is with him.

900
01:14:19,788 --> 01:14:21,915
That's his baby-sitter, right?

901
01:14:21,957 --> 01:14:24,721
Believe me. Everything is fine.

902
01:14:26,228 --> 01:14:27,957
Everything's not fine.

903
01:14:29,565 --> 01:14:30,725
Damn!

904
01:14:30,766 --> 01:14:31,994
Call security.

905
01:14:36,605 --> 01:14:38,004
Security, code yellow.

906
01:14:38,040 --> 01:14:39,234
Pediatric testing.

907
01:14:45,681 --> 01:14:48,650
This is a restricted area.
Do you have a pass?

908
01:14:48,684 --> 01:14:49,810
Screw your pass.

909
01:14:49,852 --> 01:14:51,251
It's all right.

910
01:14:51,286 --> 01:14:52,412
Where is he?

911
01:14:52,454 --> 01:14:54,285
Just stay calm.

912
01:14:54,323 --> 01:14:55,790
How's her little boy doing?

913
01:14:55,824 --> 01:14:57,382
He's fine, actually.

914
01:14:57,426 --> 01:14:59,792
He came around
about ten minutes ago.

915
01:14:59,828 --> 01:15:03,491
He seems to be suffering
from acute sleep deprivation.

916
01:15:03,532 --> 01:15:06,000
I don't think
she ever lets him sleep.

917
01:15:06,034 --> 01:15:07,331
What are you saying?

918
01:15:07,369 --> 01:15:08,597
Where is he?

919
01:15:09,972 --> 01:15:13,203
I've got someone here
who wants to see you.

920
01:15:26,488 --> 01:15:27,853
Are you OK, champ?

921
01:15:27,890 --> 01:15:29,915
Can we go get Rex now?

922
01:15:29,958 --> 01:15:32,426
The bad man's getting
awful close.

923
01:15:33,262 --> 01:15:35,196
I know he is.

924
01:15:35,230 --> 01:15:38,097
We're gonna go get Rex
right now.

925
01:15:38,133 --> 01:15:40,863
I'm afraid Dylan should
stay here until we know...

926
01:15:40,903 --> 01:15:43,497
what's causing these episodes.

927
01:15:45,641 --> 01:15:47,700
I'm sure you understand.

928
01:15:50,245 --> 01:15:51,405
Good.

929
01:15:56,318 --> 01:15:58,115
I'll tell you what.

930
01:15:58,153 --> 01:16:00,849
I'm gonna go home
and get Rex right now.

931
01:16:00,889 --> 01:16:03,050
You know that home
isn't far from here, right?

932
01:16:03,091 --> 01:16:04,752
Right across the freeway.

933
01:16:04,793 --> 01:16:05,919
That's right.

934
01:16:05,961 --> 01:16:07,428
I won't be gone long...

935
01:16:07,462 --> 01:16:10,056
and Julie's gonna stay here
with you.

936
01:16:10,098 --> 01:16:11,463
Yeah, you bet.

937
01:16:13,268 --> 01:16:16,601
Hurry up, please. I'm sleepy.

938
01:16:19,207 --> 01:16:22,074
I promise. Cross my heart.

939
01:16:22,110 --> 01:16:23,907
But, Dylan...

940
01:16:23,946 --> 01:16:26,380
until Mommy gets back...

941
01:16:26,415 --> 01:16:28,178
whatever you do...

942
01:16:28,216 --> 01:16:29,649
don't fall asleep.

943
01:16:32,287 --> 01:16:34,812
Julie, don't let him
out of your sight.

944
01:16:36,525 --> 01:16:39,585
What's going on?
Your hair's turning gray.

945
01:16:41,129 --> 01:16:43,393
Julie, keep him awake.

946
01:16:44,232 --> 01:16:46,166
Understand?

947
01:16:51,173 --> 01:16:53,801
Excuse me, miss.
Would you come with us?

948
01:16:53,842 --> 01:16:55,605
What? Hey!

949
01:16:55,644 --> 01:16:57,669
What the hell
do you think you're doing?

950
01:16:57,713 --> 01:16:59,476
Get your hands off me!

951
01:17:01,450 --> 01:17:04,078
Do you mind?
What the hell is this?

952
01:17:04,119 --> 01:17:06,110
Just a quick word...

953
01:17:06,154 --> 01:17:07,985
for Dylan's sake.

954
01:17:12,894 --> 01:17:17,126
We've had an exciting day,
haven't we?

955
01:17:18,800 --> 01:17:21,268
This one?

956
01:17:21,303 --> 01:17:23,362
Right there.

957
01:17:26,742 --> 01:17:28,437
One, two, three.
One, two, three.

958
01:17:28,477 --> 01:17:30,206
You won.

959
01:17:41,456 --> 01:17:43,720
Would you mind stepping outside
for one moment?

960
01:17:43,759 --> 01:17:46,387
As a matter of fact, I would.

961
01:17:46,428 --> 01:17:47,725
What are you doing?

962
01:17:47,763 --> 01:17:50,891
It's just a little shot
to see that he sleeps.

963
01:17:50,932 --> 01:17:52,900
No. His mother
specifically said...

964
01:17:54,036 --> 01:17:55,936
- I said no.
- Do it.

965
01:17:58,774 --> 01:18:00,036
All done.

966
01:18:02,611 --> 01:18:03,737
He'll be asleep soon.

967
01:18:03,779 --> 01:18:06,612
- Would you let go of my arm?
- You bitch!

968
01:18:09,017 --> 01:18:11,247
Hey, you can't do that!

969
01:18:14,723 --> 01:18:18,716
I know what's in that one.
Do you know what's in this one?

970
01:18:18,760 --> 01:18:21,661
Or what's gonna happen to you
when I stick you with it?

971
01:18:22,731 --> 01:18:24,494
And I will.

972
01:18:30,572 --> 01:18:34,064
I want you to stay awake, OK?

973
01:18:34,109 --> 01:18:37,044
Keep your eyes open for me.
Come on.

974
01:18:40,615 --> 01:18:43,584
Has there been any use
of recreational drugs...

975
01:18:43,618 --> 01:18:45,677
in your family?

976
01:18:45,721 --> 01:18:48,212
Or any history
of mental disturbance?

977
01:18:49,291 --> 01:18:50,553
What are you asking?

978
01:18:50,592 --> 01:18:53,152
Please, don't take it wrong.

979
01:18:53,195 --> 01:18:56,323
If there was,
there's a good chance...

980
01:18:56,364 --> 01:18:59,197
Dylan could be suffering from
something passed down to him.

981
01:19:01,002 --> 01:19:04,301
Have you been suffering
from any delusional events?

982
01:19:10,846 --> 01:19:13,076
This man from your films...

983
01:19:13,115 --> 01:19:15,140
Freddy Krueger.

984
01:19:16,585 --> 01:19:18,644
Have you been seeing him?

985
01:19:26,361 --> 01:19:28,556
Would you get those keys
down here?

986
01:19:28,597 --> 01:19:30,690
I want you to stay awake.

987
01:19:30,732 --> 01:19:32,597
Keep your eyes open for me.

988
01:19:32,634 --> 01:19:34,864
Where's Mommy?

989
01:19:34,903 --> 01:19:36,564
She'll be back. Now stay awake.

990
01:19:36,605 --> 01:19:42,066
There are drugs and treatments,
Miss Langenkamp.

991
01:19:42,110 --> 01:19:44,101
We could...

992
01:19:44,146 --> 01:19:47,309
put Dylan in foster care
for a short while.

993
01:19:47,349 --> 01:19:50,375
Just long enough to run
some tests on you.

994
01:19:50,418 --> 01:19:53,012
Keep your eyes open.
Do that for me, OK?

995
01:19:53,054 --> 01:19:56,046
Come on. You can stay awake.
Stay awake for me.

996
01:19:56,091 --> 01:19:57,718
I want you to stay awake.

997
01:19:57,759 --> 01:19:59,659
Keep your eyes open.

998
01:20:03,532 --> 01:20:05,557
Dylan, what's the matter?

999
01:20:08,436 --> 01:20:10,904
Julie, behind you.

1000
01:20:16,812 --> 01:20:19,303
There's nothing there.

1001
01:20:19,347 --> 01:20:21,645
Dylan, what's wrong?

1002
01:20:21,683 --> 01:20:25,119
Dylan, stop it.
You're scaring me.

1003
01:20:30,325 --> 01:20:32,816
I want my son out of here
right now.

1004
01:20:33,428 --> 01:20:34,986
Very well.

1005
01:20:35,030 --> 01:20:37,658
As soon as we can gather
the appropriate papers.

1006
01:20:37,699 --> 01:20:39,428
You don't understand.

1007
01:20:39,467 --> 01:20:41,458
If Dylan falls asleep, then...

1008
01:20:42,971 --> 01:20:44,404
I got it.

1009
01:20:56,852 --> 01:20:58,251
Dylan, get out of here!

1010
01:21:11,533 --> 01:21:14,024
Ever play skin the cat?

1011
01:21:26,081 --> 01:21:27,241
Come on.

1012
01:21:39,127 --> 01:21:40,389
Help me.

1013
01:21:47,402 --> 01:21:49,700
Mom!

1014
01:21:49,738 --> 01:21:53,230
Rex!

1015
01:21:53,275 --> 01:21:54,640
What the hell's going on?

1016
01:21:57,679 --> 01:21:59,670
You can't go in there. No.

1017
01:22:00,615 --> 01:22:01,809
Wait, wait.

1018
01:22:06,388 --> 01:22:08,856
Code yellow
to pediatric testing.

1019
01:22:15,931 --> 01:22:17,990
Where's my son?!

1020
01:22:18,033 --> 01:22:19,227
Where is he?!

1021
01:22:21,269 --> 01:22:22,736
Have you seen my son?

1022
01:22:22,771 --> 01:22:25,035
He was just here.

1023
01:22:25,073 --> 01:22:26,199
The boy.

1024
01:22:26,241 --> 01:22:28,937
No way he's going anywhere.
He's been heavily sedated.

1025
01:22:28,977 --> 01:22:30,911
He doesn't have to be awake
to be on his feet.

1026
01:22:30,946 --> 01:22:33,244
- What?
- He sleepwalks, you idiot.

1027
01:22:33,281 --> 01:22:36,182
He's fully capable of walking
out of this hospital.

1028
01:22:36,217 --> 01:22:37,377
Oh, shit.

1029
01:22:49,197 --> 01:22:51,529
John, it's Heather.
I need your help.

1030
01:22:52,634 --> 01:22:54,101
Why? What happened?

1031
01:22:54,135 --> 01:22:55,830
Dylan's run away
from the hospital.

1032
01:22:55,870 --> 01:22:58,566
I don't know if he's wandering
or headed for the house...

1033
01:22:58,606 --> 01:23:00,039
but I think Freddy's after him.

1034
01:23:00,075 --> 01:23:01,736
I know that sounds crazy, but...

1035
01:23:01,776 --> 01:23:03,641
You're right. That sounds crazy.

1036
01:23:05,914 --> 01:23:07,108
Oh, my God.

1037
01:23:18,426 --> 01:23:20,690
You know that home
isn't far from here, right?

1038
01:23:22,597 --> 01:23:24,292
Right across the freeway.

1039
01:24:05,306 --> 01:24:07,706
Krueger, you bastard!

1040
01:24:08,810 --> 01:24:10,004
Take me!

1041
01:24:43,278 --> 01:24:44,677
Are you OK?

1042
01:24:44,712 --> 01:24:45,872
You OK?

1043
01:24:53,721 --> 01:24:55,154
My son is out here!

1044
01:24:57,459 --> 01:24:59,791
Let me go! Dylan!

1045
01:25:38,766 --> 01:25:42,702
I'm sorry. What happened to you?
Are you all right?

1046
01:25:42,737 --> 01:25:44,602
I'm fine. Have you seen Dylan?

1047
01:25:44,639 --> 01:25:46,402
Take it easy, take it easy.

1048
01:25:46,441 --> 01:25:48,432
Relax. He's right there.
What happened?

1049
01:25:50,612 --> 01:25:52,136
Oh, God.

1050
01:25:53,148 --> 01:25:54,843
What's going on, Heather?

1051
01:25:54,883 --> 01:25:56,544
What in the world happened?

1052
01:25:57,619 --> 01:25:59,746
I know how Chase really died.

1053
01:25:59,787 --> 01:26:03,086
- What do you mean?
- Fred Krueger did it.

1054
01:26:05,860 --> 01:26:07,794
Yeah. Sure.

1055
01:26:17,939 --> 01:26:19,702
You saw him, didn't you?

1056
01:26:19,741 --> 01:26:22,335
Coming for you

1057
01:26:22,377 --> 01:26:24,470
Nancy, let's go outside.

1058
01:26:24,512 --> 01:26:26,002
He'll be all right.

1059
01:26:27,182 --> 01:26:29,047
I'll be right back.

1060
01:26:51,539 --> 01:26:53,530
What the hell is going on,
Nancy?

1061
01:26:54,943 --> 01:26:57,878
Why are you calling me Nancy,
John?

1062
01:26:57,912 --> 01:27:00,073
Why are you calling me John?

1063
01:27:06,020 --> 01:27:07,851
Nancy, pull yourself together...

1064
01:27:07,889 --> 01:27:10,187
before you make yourself
and that kid nuts.

1065
01:27:18,366 --> 01:27:20,061
Would you call Robert?

1066
01:27:21,069 --> 01:27:22,366
Robert Englund.

1067
01:27:24,105 --> 01:27:26,335
- The guy who plays Freddy.
- Freddy who?

1068
01:27:26,374 --> 01:27:27,773
Freddy Krueger.

1069
01:27:29,711 --> 01:27:32,544
Nancy, Freddy's dead.

1070
01:27:37,118 --> 01:27:40,747
Don't start losing it
like your mother did.

1071
01:27:41,789 --> 01:27:43,950
I love you, sweetheart.

1072
01:27:45,994 --> 01:27:47,256
Don't forget that.

1073
01:27:56,204 --> 01:27:58,365
I love you, too...

1074
01:27:58,406 --> 01:27:59,566
Daddy.

1075
01:28:27,669 --> 01:28:31,196
Get yourself some rest,
Nancy, please.

1076
01:29:04,405 --> 01:29:09,707
One, two,
Freddy's coming for you

1077
01:29:18,119 --> 01:29:20,144
Who's there?

1078
01:29:22,390 --> 01:29:25,587
Listen, Daddy.
I've got a proposition for you.

1079
01:29:25,626 --> 01:29:27,753
I'm gonna get the guy
who did it...

1080
01:29:27,795 --> 01:29:30,764
and I want you to arrest him
when I bring him out, OK?

1081
01:29:30,798 --> 01:29:34,461
Nancy, just tell me who did it.
I'll go get him, baby.

1082
01:29:34,502 --> 01:29:36,265
Fred Krueger did it, Daddy.

1083
01:29:36,304 --> 01:29:37,737
Yeah, sure.

1084
01:30:11,038 --> 01:30:13,336
Dylan's sleeping pills.

1085
01:30:14,208 --> 01:30:16,699
Say how they find
their way back home.

1086
01:30:16,744 --> 01:30:18,302
It's important.

1087
01:30:20,248 --> 01:30:21,442
Breadcrumbs.

1088
01:30:26,687 --> 01:30:27,881
Too late, Heather.

1089
01:30:29,424 --> 01:30:31,415
Too late.

1090
01:31:29,784 --> 01:31:31,809
Join you.

1091
01:31:33,421 --> 01:31:36,083
You've given me a way
to join you.

1092
01:34:15,683 --> 01:34:18,675
Almost there.

1093
01:34:59,960 --> 01:35:03,054
"The more she read,
the more she realized...

1094
01:35:03,097 --> 01:35:06,498
"what she had in her hands
was nothing more or less...

1095
01:35:06,534 --> 01:35:08,798
"than her life itself.

1096
01:35:08,836 --> 01:35:11,862
"That everything she had
experienced and thought...

1097
01:35:11,906 --> 01:35:14,170
"was bound within these pages."

1098
01:35:16,844 --> 01:35:19,244
"There was no movie.

1099
01:35:19,280 --> 01:35:22,443
"There was only... her life."

1100
01:35:24,151 --> 01:35:25,846
It's just me.

1101
01:35:30,324 --> 01:35:32,622
Are you OK? Are you all right?

1102
01:35:33,327 --> 01:35:34,453
Where's the man?

1103
01:35:34,495 --> 01:35:36,122
I don't know.

1104
01:35:36,163 --> 01:35:38,859
He had me,
but then he let me go.

1105
01:35:42,103 --> 01:35:43,900
Meet your maker.

1106
01:35:55,049 --> 01:35:57,040
Pick a pet for the rugrat,
bitch.

1107
01:36:08,596 --> 01:36:10,257
Fuck you!

1108
01:36:13,868 --> 01:36:15,699
Get over there, Dylan!

1109
01:36:37,458 --> 01:36:38,686
Take this!

1110
01:36:51,172 --> 01:36:54,073
Come here, my piggy.
I got some gingerbread for you.

1111
01:37:14,495 --> 01:37:15,655
Gotcha!

1112
01:37:28,843 --> 01:37:32,335
Where's your mommy,
piglet, huh, huh?

1113
01:37:33,881 --> 01:37:38,011
One, two,
Freddy's coming for you!

1114
01:39:14,915 --> 01:39:16,576
Come to papa.

1115
01:39:21,288 --> 01:39:23,085
Gonna eat you up.

1116
01:39:40,274 --> 01:39:42,708
Leave him alone!

1117
01:40:04,698 --> 01:40:07,166
Dylan, get out of there!

1118
01:41:05,325 --> 01:41:06,485
Push!

1119
01:41:33,353 --> 01:41:34,615
Run!

1120
01:42:07,688 --> 01:42:08,882
Are you OK?

1121
01:42:14,728 --> 01:42:16,662
Honey, honey.

1122
01:42:19,766 --> 01:42:21,666
Oh, my God.

1123
01:42:21,702 --> 01:42:24,933
We're saved. The witch is dead.

1124
01:42:24,972 --> 01:42:28,339
And his mother covered him
with kisses, and they were safe.

1125
01:42:40,154 --> 01:42:41,451
"Heather...

1126
01:42:41,488 --> 01:42:44,321
"thanks for having the guts
to play Nancy one last time.

1127
01:42:44,358 --> 01:42:47,885
"At last Freddy's back
where he belongs.

1128
01:42:47,928 --> 01:42:49,896
"Regards, Wes."

1129
01:43:05,479 --> 01:43:07,879
Is it a story?

1130
01:43:07,915 --> 01:43:10,907
Yeah. It's a story.

1131
01:43:10,951 --> 01:43:12,680
Read me some.

1132
01:43:15,522 --> 01:43:18,685
"We open on an old wooden bench.

1133
01:43:18,725 --> 01:43:21,421
"There's fire and tools...

1134
01:43:21,461 --> 01:43:23,691
"and a man's grimy hands...

1135
01:43:23,730 --> 01:43:28,531
"building what soon is revealed
as a gleaming set of claws.

1136
01:43:28,569 --> 01:43:30,901
"And the claws are moving now...

1137
01:43:30,938 --> 01:43:35,966
"as if awakening
from a long and unwanted sleep.

1138
01:43:36,009 --> 01:43:39,968
"Then the man lays one trembling
hand flat upon the table...

1139
01:43:40,013 --> 01:43:44,279
"and with his other
picks up a thick, sharp blade.

1140
01:43:44,318 --> 01:43:49,051
"Behind the lights,
faces watch from the darkness...

1141
01:43:49,089 --> 01:43:53,526
"ready to laugh
or scream in terror."

